<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet xml:id="lt1-practice-quiz">
  <title>Learning Target 1: Sketching Qualitative Graphs</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>I can sketch qualitative graphs with appropriate variable definitions.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <!-- ============================================================
       PROBLEM 1: Water glass at a restaurant
       ============================================================ -->
  <page>
    <exercise xml:id="lt1-water-glass">
      <title>A Glass of Water</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Read the following story carefully. Then sketch a graph that shows how the amount of
          water in the glass changes over time.
        </p>
        <p>
          A server brings a full glass of water to a table. For the first 5 minutes, nobody
          touches it. Over the next 3 minutes, the person at the table takes three quick drinks,
          each one reducing the amount of water in the glass noticeably. For the next 5 minutes
          after that, no more drinks are taken. Then the server comes by with a pitcher and
          refills the glass back to full.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            What are the two quantities being graphed? Identify the input and the output,
            including units.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            The input (independent variable) is time, measured in minutes. The output
            (dependent variable) is the amount of water in the glass, which could be measured
            in ounces or as a percent of the glass's capacity. The amount of water depends on
            how much time has passed.
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>

      <task workspace="3.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Sketch a graph of the amount of water in the glass over time. Label the horizontal
            axis with time and the vertical axis with the amount of water. Your graph does not
            need exact numbers, but it should clearly show the shape of each part of the story.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Hint:</em> Think about each part of the story one at a time. Is the water level
            rising, falling, or staying the same during each part?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            A sample graph is shown below. The key features are: the graph starts at a high
            value (full glass) and stays flat for the first 5 minutes. It then drops three
            times in quick steps over the next 3 minutes, with brief flat stretches between
            each drop (representing the pauses between drinks). It then stays flat for 5
            more minutes (no drinks taken). Finally, it rises sharply back to the original
            high value (the refill).
          </p>
          <image width="80%">
            <shortdescription>
              A sample sketch for the water glass story: the graph starts high and flat for
              5 minutes, drops in three steps over the next 3 minutes (with brief flat
              stretches between drops), stays flat for 5 more minutes, then jumps back up
              to the starting level.
            </shortdescription>
            <description>
              <p>
                A graph with time in minutes on the horizontal axis (0 to 14) and amount of
                water as a percent on the vertical axis (0 to 100). The line starts at 100
                percent and stays flat to minute 5. It drops to 75 at minute 5.5, stays flat
                briefly, drops to 50 at minute 7, stays flat briefly, drops to 25 at minute
                8, stays flat to minute 13, then rises sharply back to 100 at minute 13.
              </p>
            </description>
            <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="lt1-water-glass-answer">
              <diagram dimensions="(520,320)" margins="(60,50,130,18)">
                <coordinates bbox="(-0.6,-8,14.5,108)">
                  <grid-axes hticks="(0,1,14)" vticks="(0,25,100)" h-zero-label="yes">
                    <xlabel alignment="se">Time (minutes)</xlabel>
                    <ylabel alignment="ne">Water in glass (%)</ylabel>
                  </grid-axes>
                  <polygon points="((0,100),(5,100),(5.5,75),(6,75),(7,50),(7.5,50),(8,25),(13,25),(13,100),(14,100))" stroke="purple" thickness="3"/>
                  <point p="(0,100)" size="3" fill="purple"/>
                  <point p="(14,100)" size="3" fill="purple"/>
                </coordinates>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure>
          </image>
        </answer>
      </task>

      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Describe what the flat (horizontal) parts of your graph represent in terms of the
            story. What is happening to the water level during those times?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Each horizontal segment means the water level is not changing during that
            interval. There are three such stretches in this story: the first 5 minutes while
            nobody drinks, the brief pauses between each of the three drinks, and the
            5-minute stretch after the last drink before the refill.
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>

      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            What does it mean that the graph goes up sharply near the end? Why is it so steep?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            The sharp upward jump represents the refill: the server pours water quickly from
            a pitcher, so the water level rises back to full in a very short amount of time.
            A steep upward slope means the quantity is increasing rapidly. If the refill took
            much longer, the rising segment would be less steep.
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>

  <!-- ============================================================
       PROBLEM 2: Phone battery
       ============================================================ -->
  <page>
    <exercise xml:id="lt1-phone-battery">
      <title>A Phone Battery</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Read the following story carefully. Then sketch a graph that shows how the phone's
          battery level changes over time.
        </p>
        <p>
          You take your phone off its charger with the battery at about half charge. The battery
          drains slowly over the next few hours while the phone sits mostly idle. You then plug
          it in and charge it rapidly for about an hour until it reaches full charge. After
          unplugging it again, you stream music for several hours, which drains the battery
          noticeably faster than when it was idle.
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            What are the two quantities being graphed? Identify the input and the output,
            including units.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            The input (independent variable) is time, measured in hours. The output
            (dependent variable) is the battery charge, measured as a percent of full charge.
            The battery level depends on how much time has passed and what the phone is doing.
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>

      <task workspace="3.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Sketch a graph of the battery level over time. Label the horizontal axis with time
            in hours and the vertical axis with the battery charge as a percent (0 to 100).
            Your graph should clearly show the three distinct phases of the story.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Hint:</em> Think about what is different between each phase. Is the battery going
            up or down? Is the change fast or slow?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            A sample graph is shown below. The three phases are: a gradual decline from about
            50 percent down toward 20 percent (idle drain, slow slope downward); a steep rise
            from 20 percent back to 100 percent over about one hour (rapid charging); and
            then a steeper decline than the first phase as music streaming drains the battery
            more quickly.
          </p>
          <image width="80%">
            <shortdescription>
              A sample sketch for the phone battery story: the graph starts at 50 percent and
              declines slowly for 3 hours to about 20 percent, then rises steeply over 1 hour
              to 100 percent, then declines at a steeper rate than the first phase over the
              next 3 hours to about 25 percent.
            </shortdescription>
            <description>
              <p>
                A graph with time in hours on the horizontal axis (0 to 7) and battery charge
                as a percent on the vertical axis (0 to 100). The line starts at 50 percent
                at hour 0 and declines gradually to 20 percent at hour 3. It then rises
                steeply to 100 percent at hour 4. From hour 4 it declines at a noticeably
                steeper rate than the first segment, reaching about 25 percent by hour 7.
              </p>
            </description>
            <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="lt1-battery-answer">
              <diagram dimensions="(520,320)" margins="(60,50,130,18)">
                <coordinates bbox="(-0.3,-8,7.4,108)">
                  <grid-axes hticks="(0,1,7)" vticks="(0,20,100)" h-zero-label="yes">
                    <xlabel alignment="se">Time (hours)</xlabel>
                    <ylabel alignment="ne">Battery charge (%)</ylabel>
                  </grid-axes>
                  <polygon points="((0,50),(3,20),(4,100),(7,25))" stroke="purple" thickness="3"/>
                  <point p="(0,50)" size="3" fill="purple"/>
                  <point p="(3,20)" size="3" fill="purple"/>
                  <point p="(4,100)" size="3" fill="purple"/>
                </coordinates>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure>
          </image>
        </answer>
      </task>

      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            How does the slope of the graph during the streaming phase compare to the slope
            during the idle phase? What does that difference in slope mean for the story?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            Both segments slope downward, but the streaming segment is steeper. A steeper
            downward slope means the battery is losing charge more quickly. During the idle
            phase, the phone uses very little power so the battery drains slowly. During
            streaming, the screen, processor, and network are all active, so the battery
            drains at a faster rate.
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>

      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Identify the highest point on your graph. What does it represent in terms of the
            story, and when does it occur?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            The highest point is at 100 percent charge, occurring at hour 4, right when the
            phone is unplugged after being charged. This is the moment the battery is
            completely full. Before this point the charge was rising (charging); after this
            point it begins falling again (streaming drains it).
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>

</worksheet>
